# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation Report

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the React/Vite portfolio project following the latest official Vercel documentation.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version 2.0.0 using npm
- Updated `package.json` with the new dependency
- Updated `package-lock.json` with the new dependency tree

### 2. Code Configuration
**Modified: `src/App.jsx`**
- Added import statement: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/react'`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the root App component's return statement
- Placed the component after the BrowserRouter to ensure it loads on all routes

## Implementation Details

The implementation follows the official Vercel Speed Insights quickstart guide:
- Documentation source: https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart
- Framework-specific integration for React was used
- The SpeedInsights component was added to the root App component to track performance across all pages

## Verification

✅ **Build**: Successfully compiled with `npm run build`
- Build completed in 352ms
- No build errors or warnings
- Output size: ~277KB JS bundle + ~31KB CSS

✅ **Linter**: Passed ESLint checks with no errors or warnings

✅ **Dependencies**: Lock file (package-lock.json) updated correctly

## Next Steps for User

To complete the Speed Insights setup:
1. Enable Speed Insights in your Vercel dashboard
   - Navigate to your project in Vercel
   - Select "Speed Insights" from the sidebar
   - Click "Enable" for this project
2. Deploy the application to Vercel using `vercel deploy`
3. After deployment, verify the tracking script appears in your page's head tag
4. Monitor performance metrics in the Vercel Speed Insights dashboard after users visit your site

## Technical Notes

- The SpeedInsights component is a lightweight React component that automatically tracks Core Web Vitals
- It will only send data when deployed on Vercel
- No configuration is required for basic functionality
- The component has minimal performance impact on the application
